00:00:01,090 --> 00:00:02,340
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:02,340 --> 00:00:05,880
On board the Parvina

3
00:00:05,880 --> 00:00:10,920
Leaning on the rail at the stern of the cruise
ship Parvina, sipping his champagne, Eddie

4
00:00:10,920 --> 00:00:17,580
Munro looked out across the water and into
the darkness. There was a warm, gentle breeze,

5
00:00:17,580 --> 00:00:22,660
and the sea was calm except for the dizzy
trail of water churned up by the ship's angry

6
00:00:22,660 --> 00:00:28,580
propellers. It was a beautiful evening and
there was no one else on deck. Eddie liked

7
00:00:28,580 --> 00:00:31,190
it that way.

8
00:00:31,190 --> 00:00:36,250
He looked down at his watch, which showed
10.31 p.m., and the ship was already half

9
00:00:36,250 --> 00:00:42,699
a mile from the harbour. He was amazed that
such a huge cruise ship could move so fast

10
00:00:42,699 --> 00:00:48,540
- he was amazed it stayed afloat at all! He
watched St Thomas island getting further and

11
00:00:48,540 --> 00:00:53,840
further away. He stared at the silhouette
of the island, at its faint black shapes of

12
00:00:53,840 --> 00:01:00,480
hills rising up into the night sky. Eddie
smiled to himself as he noticed he could no

13
00:01:00,480 --> 00:01:05,600
longer see where the lights ended and the
stars began.

14
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:11,679
He finished his champagne and, for good luck,
threw the glass far out into the sea. He never

15
00:01:11,679 --> 00:01:17,170
heard it drop. He couldn't see much at all
in the warm Caribbean darkness, but he noticed

16
00:01:17,170 --> 00:01:25,329
for the first time how high up he was. The
sea was a long, long way down, he thought.

17
00:01:25,329 --> 00:01:30,590
At this point his wife, Lynn, came out looking
for him, wearing her long black evening dress

18
00:01:30,590 --> 00:01:35,810
and the silk purple scarf she had bought on
the excursion earlier in the day. Her hair

19
00:01:35,810 --> 00:01:40,280
was dark and short with plum-coloured highlights.

20
00:01:40,280 --> 00:01:45,840
He turned to put his arm around her as she
joined him. He noticed her perfume, a powerful

21
00:01:45,840 --> 00:01:47,929
and luxurious scent.

22
00:01:47,929 --> 00:01:55,640
"Hello," he said, turning round. "You smell
nice. And you look lovely. Are you married?"

23
00:01:55,640 --> 00:02:02,309
"Yes, thank you. To a very wealthy man, so
you have no chance," she said, smiling.

24
00:02:02,309 --> 00:02:05,189
"Ah. But so am I."

25
00:02:05,189 --> 00:02:09,209
"Ah, so you're married to a wealthy man, are
you?"

26
00:02:09,209 --> 00:02:13,510
"I mean I'm wealthy. Very rich, in fact."

27
00:02:13,510 --> 00:02:17,290
"Well aren't you the lucky one," Lynn said.

28
00:02:17,290 --> 00:02:22,989
"Yes, so if you're lucky, I might buy you
dinner," said Eddie, turning back to look

29
00:02:22,989 --> 00:02:24,870
out to sea once more.

30
00:02:24,870 --> 00:02:32,409
"Well, lucky me. How can I refuse such charm?"
She looked at him and took hold of his hand.

31
00:02:32,409 --> 00:02:37,709
She smiled and stared out into the night,
too, to the island which was now even further

32
00:02:37,709 --> 00:02:38,799
away.

33
00:02:38,799 --> 00:02:44,299
"I thought I'd find you out here," she said.
"How many glasses have you thrown into the

34
00:02:44,299 --> 00:02:45,340
sea this evening?"

35
00:02:45,340 --> 00:02:47,569
"Only two," he said.

36
00:02:47,569 --> 00:02:48,569
"Eddie!"

37
00:02:48,569 --> 00:02:49,819
"It's good luck."

38
00:02:49,819 --> 00:02:54,400
"No, it isn't. Not if you're a fish and you
get hit by a glass."

39
00:02:54,400 --> 00:02:59,629
"The fish might like it. It's probably quite
boring being a fish. The sudden arrival of

40
00:02:59,629 --> 00:03:02,349
a champagne glass might brighten up your life."

41
00:03:02,349 --> 00:03:04,969
"Or end it," she said.

42
00:03:04,969 --> 00:03:08,269
"It's fun," said Eddie. "You should try it."

43
00:03:08,269 --> 00:03:11,650
"I think I've had enough champagne," his wife
said.

44
00:03:11,650 --> 00:03:18,430
"I love the way the glass disappears the minute
it leaves my hand, and the sea eats it up.

45
00:03:18,430 --> 00:03:22,680
You can't see it falling and you can't hear
it hit the water. But you know it's landed,

46
00:03:22,680 --> 00:03:28,700
dived in and sunk to the bottom. Imagine - a
tiny glass holding a giant ocean."

47
00:03:28,700 --> 00:03:36,319
"You think too much," she said, moving away
and pulling him with her. "Why don't you come

48
00:03:36,319 --> 00:03:40,950
back inside? They're serving coffee and I
think there's going to be some jazz."

49
00:03:40,950 --> 00:03:44,420
"All right," he said. "Just a few more minutes."

50
00:03:44,420 --> 00:03:50,150
"We have two more weeks on this cruise, Eddie.
You have plenty of time to take it all in."

51
00:03:50,150 --> 00:03:56,139
"It's incredible, though, isn't it? So beautiful.
It's perfect."

52
00:03:56,139 --> 00:04:01,430
Lynn laughed. "It's completely black. I can't
see anything in the dark."

53
00:04:01,430 --> 00:04:08,200
"I know. But it's all out there. The blue
sea, the white sand, the palm trees, the boats..."

54
00:04:08,200 --> 00:04:09,879
"The champagne glasses..."

55
00:04:09,879 --> 00:04:16,160
"Very funny," said Eddie. Then he pointed
to the horizon. "Look over there at the dots

56
00:04:16,160 --> 00:04:22,880
of light. Do you think they're lights on the
island or stars?"

57
00:04:22,880 --> 00:04:28,310
Lynn looked hard into the night and gave it
some thought. "Erm... lights."

58
00:04:28,310 --> 00:04:31,449
"But you're not sure."

59
00:04:31,449 --> 00:04:34,199
"I am sure. I'm always sure."

60
00:04:34,199 --> 00:04:38,430
"Hmm," he said. "How is that?"

61
00:04:38,430 --> 00:04:42,009
"Because I'm always right," she said, smiling.

62
00:04:42,009 --> 00:04:43,250
"Oh really?"

63
00:04:43,250 --> 00:04:48,820
"Of course. I was right about setting up your
own business, wasn't I?"

64
00:04:48,820 --> 00:04:49,820
"Yes."

65
00:04:49,820 --> 00:04:54,650
"And I was right about selling the business
off this year for twenty million - only sixteen

66
00:04:54,650 --> 00:04:55,810
years after starting."

67
00:04:55,810 --> 00:05:00,819
"Possibly," he teased. He wouldn't give in
so easily.

68
00:05:00,819 --> 00:05:06,620
"And I was right to let you take me on this
cruise to relax and celebrate in style."

69
00:05:06,620 --> 00:05:10,110
"Oh, I see. How generous."

70
00:05:10,110 --> 00:05:16,830
"Just think. You don't have to work ever again.
You're a millionaire, Mr Edward Munro. How

71
00:05:16,830 --> 00:05:18,740
does that sound?"

72
00:05:18,740 --> 00:05:21,639
"Lucky me," he said proudly.

73
00:05:21,639 --> 00:05:28,400
"Yes, lucky you. Lucky us. Now come inside
before we lose all our money paying for missing

74
00:05:28,400 --> 00:05:32,620
champagne glasses."

75
00:05:32,620 --> 00:05:38,479
Back inside, the dining room was full of people.
It was hot, but the lighting made it welcoming

76
00:05:38,479 --> 00:05:44,270
and comfortable. In the time Eddie had been
outside, a space had been cleared for dancing

77
00:05:44,270 --> 00:05:50,060
and a few couples were already on their feet.
In the corner, four musicians, three men and

78
00:05:50,060 --> 00:05:55,930
one woman, were playing a song Eddie knew
well, but he couldn't recall its name. The

79
00:05:55,930 --> 00:06:01,599
singer was wearing a navy blue cocktail dress,
and the men were wearing tuxedos, black ties

80
00:06:01,599 --> 00:06:05,050
and formal dinner suits.

81
00:06:05,050 --> 00:06:09,720
Eddie noticed how young the woman looked.
Too young to have known the tune when it first

82
00:06:09,720 --> 00:06:14,960
appeared, Eddie thought, but her voice was
strong and clear. And she seemed to believe

83
00:06:14,960 --> 00:06:22,080
in the words, at least. How old was she? Twenty-five?
Twenty-six? Imagine singing on a cruise ship

84
00:06:22,080 --> 00:06:28,479
in your twenties! What a life! The fun, the
parties, the people. The places to go and

85
00:06:28,479 --> 00:06:32,630
things to see - before your life had even
started.

86
00:06:32,630 --> 00:06:39,409
It seems so easy now, Eddie thought. His twenties
had been very different. And his thirties.

87
00:06:39,409 --> 00:06:45,160
Eddie tried not to think about his own past.
Now was all that mattered. The past was the

88
00:06:45,160 --> 00:06:50,949
past. 'What doesn't kill you makes you stronger,'
Clive, his business partner, always said.

89
00:06:50,949 --> 00:06:56,750
'No such thing as luck,' he once said, 'it's
simply the moment when preparation meets opportunity.'

90
00:06:56,750 --> 00:07:03,389
By now, Eddie was sitting back at his table
and next to his wife. She was watching the

91
00:07:03,389 --> 00:07:08,759
band and tapping the table. She smiled at
the other passengers opposite her, who smiled

92
00:07:08,759 --> 00:07:15,599
back, relaxed and enjoying the moment. Eddie
looked at his watch. It was almost 11 p.m.,

93
00:07:15,599 --> 00:07:21,280
but he wasn't tired. Quite the opposite. He
felt relaxed and energized. He'd always been

94
00:07:21,280 --> 00:07:25,060
an evening person, never a morning person.

95
00:07:25,060 --> 00:07:29,689
He looked around at the giant lounge with
its circular tables and well-dressed diners,

96
00:07:29,689 --> 00:07:34,970
and the perfect white tablecloths. The waiters
and waitresses in their smart uniforms moved

97
00:07:34,970 --> 00:07:40,030
smoothly in and out of the room, and Eddie's
eyes followed them as they carried plates

98
00:07:40,030 --> 00:07:46,930
and coffee and cakes and trays around the
tables, along the aisles and past the bar.

99
00:07:46,930 --> 00:07:51,570
Eddie watched the barman throwing ice cubes
and cocktail shakers in the air and juggling

100
00:07:51,570 --> 00:07:58,479
them as he made the drinks in acrobatic style.
He was confident and polished, and also young.

101
00:07:58,479 --> 00:08:05,120
Possibly the same age as the singer. Why was
everyone so young these days? Where were all

102
00:08:05,120 --> 00:08:10,570
the cruise ship jobs when Eddie was trying
to get started in life? Why hadn't he thought

103
00:08:10,570 --> 00:08:14,270
of working on a ship in the Caribbean?

104
00:08:14,270 --> 00:08:19,110
He found himself staring at the bar in the
distance. He was no longer thinking of anything

105
00:08:19,110 --> 00:08:23,889
in particular. He was simply listening to
the sounds of jazz and the noise of a few

106
00:08:23,889 --> 00:08:26,409
hundred people talking and laughing.

107
00:08:26,409 --> 00:08:29,930
And that was when he saw him.

108
00:08:29,930 --> 00:08:36,011
That was the moment when he saw Dominic for
the first time in many, many years. The man

109
00:08:36,011 --> 00:08:43,080
was sitting at the bar, leaning forward and
smoking a large cigar. He was older now, clearly,

110
00:08:43,080 --> 00:08:48,970
and his hair was very grey, but Eddie had
no doubt that it was him. He couldn't believe

111
00:08:48,970 --> 00:08:51,920
that awful man was here on the ship.

112
00:08:51,920 --> 00:08:54,190
And then everything was different.

113
00:08:54,190 --> 00:08:58,600
Nothing was the same. All was spoiled.

114
00:08:58,600 --> 00:09:00,510
Just like before.

115
00:09:00,510 --> 00:09:02,960
CHAPTER TWO
Argument with Dominic

116
00:09:02,960 --> 00:09:12,070
"You know your problem, Eddie?" said Dominic
Stephens in his office. "You're too hands-on."

117
00:09:12,070 --> 00:09:17,970
He leaned back in his large, leather chair
behind his glass desk. He seldom made eye

118
00:09:17,970 --> 00:09:21,530
contact. His shoulders looked tense and his
neck was hidden.

119
00:09:21,530 --> 00:09:27,290
"I don't understand," said Eddie. "How can
that be a problem? The team really appreciates

120
00:09:27,290 --> 00:09:32,120
my style and the customers love it. It's what
I do best. It's why I was brought here in

121
00:09:32,120 --> 00:09:33,440
the first place."

122
00:09:33,440 --> 00:09:36,790
"Oh, really?" said Dominic, clearly unimpressed.

123
00:09:36,790 --> 00:09:42,210
"I know for a fact that Ann and Gary didn't
want an executive to run things. They wanted

124
00:09:42,210 --> 00:09:49,200
someone with practical experience, and drive
- and lots of it. They said dull and uninspiring

125
00:09:49,200 --> 00:09:54,401
executives and managers have come and gone
and there's been no direction, no feeling

126
00:09:54,401 --> 00:09:55,940
for the business. No passion."

127
00:09:55,940 --> 00:09:59,690
"And you have passion?" said Dominic.

128
00:09:59,690 --> 00:10:01,350
"Yes. Do you?"

129
00:10:01,350 --> 00:10:07,190
"This isn't about me, Eddie. It's about you,
and it takes more than passion to do this

130
00:10:07,190 --> 00:10:09,420
job. You need to be a leader."

131
00:10:09,420 --> 00:10:16,920
"I am a leader," replied Eddie. "I've done
it for years. My track record speaks for itself."

132
00:10:16,920 --> 00:10:19,120
"Well, you can't do it all by yourself."

133
00:10:19,120 --> 00:10:26,460
"I'm not trying to do it all by myself, Dominic.
I'm building a team. I'm training new people.

134
00:10:26,460 --> 00:10:28,730
Resources are limited. It takes time."

135
00:10:28,730 --> 00:10:32,380
"We don't have time, Eddie."

136
00:10:32,380 --> 00:10:37,970
What did Dominic Stephens know about passion
or time? wondered Eddie. The only passion

137
00:10:37,970 --> 00:10:43,700
he seemed to have was being in charge. And
golf. He seemed to have a lot of time for

138
00:10:43,700 --> 00:10:49,910
that. He even kept his clubs in the corner
of his office. And today was Thursday. On

139
00:10:49,910 --> 00:10:55,770
Thursdays he always left early to play golf
and he didn't even try to hide it.

140
00:10:55,770 --> 00:11:02,580
Eddie was so angry his mouth was dry. "I don't
know why you have a problem with me, Dominic.

141
00:11:02,580 --> 00:11:06,410
There's nothing wrong with my performance.
Quite the opposite in fact."

142
00:11:06,410 --> 00:11:08,150
"Oh, really?"

143
00:11:08,150 --> 00:11:12,950
"Yes. When I joined Fenton's, they were only
producing software for small businesses in

144
00:11:12,950 --> 00:11:18,570
the UK. They had some accounting packages
and sales and marketing databases, but not

145
00:11:18,570 --> 00:11:24,510
much else. I was brought in to expand the
business and build exports, and that is exactly

146
00:11:24,510 --> 00:11:30,360
what I have done. I brought in some very talented
people to develop our products, and we now

147
00:11:30,360 --> 00:11:36,950
offer some unique and very powerful programs
used by the biggest and best companies globally.

148
00:11:36,950 --> 00:11:42,660
When I proposed and won the Moscow account,
you said it couldn't be done, and now we supply

149
00:11:42,660 --> 00:11:44,380
the entire Russian region."

150
00:11:44,380 --> 00:11:53,070
"Erm, excuse me, Mr Passion. I won the Moscow
contract for you," said Dominic, pointing

151
00:11:53,070 --> 00:11:55,580
firmly at his own chest.

152
00:11:55,580 --> 00:12:02,260
Eddie could not believe his ears. This was
so unfair. Rage filled his whole mind and

153
00:12:02,260 --> 00:12:07,900
body. "You did not win that contract. You
knew some of the people in the Russian state

154
00:12:07,900 --> 00:12:12,950
department there, that's all. I spent most
of last year - and the year before - going

155
00:12:12,950 --> 00:12:18,410
to Russia and working long, long hours to
build a business plan that would work. Don't

156
00:12:18,410 --> 00:12:23,200
take the credit away from me, Dominic. Without
me, this company could never have won such

157
00:12:23,200 --> 00:12:25,140
a high-profile project."

158
00:12:25,140 --> 00:12:29,960
"Well, I still haven't seen the final numbers,
and I still haven't seen the new business

159
00:12:29,960 --> 00:12:33,510
plan," Dominic said, throwing his arms around.

160
00:12:33,510 --> 00:12:38,820
"Yes, you have. I've kept you informed the
whole time with numerous emails."

161
00:12:38,820 --> 00:12:46,240
"Oh, emails, emails! I don't have time for
emails. I get about three hundred a day. How

162
00:12:46,240 --> 00:12:48,840
on earth can I keep up with all that?"

163
00:12:48,840 --> 00:12:54,110
Well, it would help if you didn't play so
much golf, Eddie wanted to say. It would help

164
00:12:54,110 --> 00:12:59,610
if you let me do my job and didn't interfere.
It would help if you weren't so aggressive.

165
00:12:59,610 --> 00:13:06,290
Instead, he tried to remain diplomatic and
said, "Well, if you don't read my emails,

166
00:13:06,290 --> 00:13:07,620
how can we communicate?"

167
00:13:07,620 --> 00:13:11,690
"Simple. Pick up the phone."

168
00:13:11,690 --> 00:13:18,260
He made it sound so easy. This was ridiculous.
"I do call you, Dominic. You're never there.

169
00:13:18,260 --> 00:13:23,220
I leave messages but you don't call back.
When we do get time to meet, I don't think

170
00:13:23,220 --> 00:13:24,220
you're really listening."

171
00:13:24,220 --> 00:13:31,701
"I'm always listening to you, Eddie," said
Dominic in a weary voice. "Because you talk

172
00:13:31,701 --> 00:13:37,680
so much, that's all you ever do. Talk, talk,
talk."

173
00:13:37,680 --> 00:13:43,370
"You're making personal comments, and that
is not professional. I talk because I'm passionate.

174
00:13:43,370 --> 00:13:48,830
And I deliver. If I say I'll do something,
I do it, and within budget, and you know it."

175
00:13:48,830 --> 00:13:55,200
"You were not on budget. Last year you went
over budget by 25,000 pounds"

176
00:13:55,200 --> 00:14:01,990
Not this again. Eddie was so tired of the
same story. "I can account for every penny

177
00:14:01,990 --> 00:14:07,980
my department spent. No one seems to know
what happened to that 25,000 pounds."

178
00:14:07,980 --> 00:14:09,750
Dominic looked at him accusingly.

179
00:14:09,750 --> 00:14:13,320
"Don't look at me like that," said Eddie.

180
00:14:13,320 --> 00:14:15,160
"Like what?"

181
00:14:15,160 --> 00:14:21,650
"Look, the way I see it..." Eddie began, but
again he was cut off in mid-sentence. Dominic

182
00:14:21,650 --> 00:14:26,410
always interrupted everyone. He was like a
spoilt child.

183
00:14:26,410 --> 00:14:32,080
And so the situation was impossible. Eddie
simply wanted to leave. He could no longer

184
00:14:32,080 --> 00:14:35,930
focus. He could never win.

185
00:14:35,930 --> 00:14:40,500
Eddie came out of the office. His whole body
was trembling, and he tried very hard not

186
00:14:40,500 --> 00:14:46,560
to slam the door, scream or break something.
He realized he was too angry and too upset

187
00:14:46,560 --> 00:14:52,530
to go back to the team or finish his work.
He decided to slip out of the office for ten

188
00:14:52,530 --> 00:14:59,620
minutes, just to calm down. He would have
a coffee. Or call Lynn. Come on, Ed, he told

189
00:14:59,620 --> 00:15:04,940
himself. Get things in perspective. It's only
a job.

190
00:15:04,940 --> 00:15:09,700
He was almost at reception and the main door,
when Clive passed him on the way to the photocopier.

191
00:15:09,700 --> 00:15:15,200
"Ed, what's wrong?" he asked, stopping in
the corridor.

192
00:15:15,200 --> 00:15:19,560
Eddie couldn't speak. He was afraid to say
anything, as he didn't know what might come

193
00:15:19,560 --> 00:15:26,950
out. His face was red and tears were stinging
his eyes. He looked down, ignored Clive and

194
00:15:26,950 --> 00:15:31,990
walked out of the door into the street and
towards the local cafe.

195
00:15:31,990 --> 00:15:34,440
CHAPTER THREE
Someone from the past

196
00:15:34,440 --> 00:15:42,490
"You all right, Eddie?" asked Lynn, who had
noticed Eddie staring at the bar. Eddie took

197
00:15:42,490 --> 00:15:49,500
a moment and then said, "Yes, fine. Why?"
But he was still lost in thought. He wasn't

198
00:15:49,500 --> 00:15:52,580
sure if the ship was moving or if he was dizzy.

199
00:15:52,580 --> 00:15:57,130
"You look so serious. Come on, let's dance."

200
00:15:57,130 --> 00:16:03,950
He was still staring at the bar. The man was
still there. It was Dominic. Sitting at the

201
00:16:03,950 --> 00:16:10,061
bar barely fifty meters away, drinking and
smoking. As simple as that. Was the world

202
00:16:10,061 --> 00:16:16,190
so small? thought Eddie. Couldn't it be a
bit bigger? Why here? Why now? After all this

203
00:16:16,190 --> 00:16:22,090
time. Why on this ship? A familiar sickness
in his stomach returned.

204
00:16:22,090 --> 00:16:26,840
"Well, don't get too excited, will you?" Eddie
heard his wife say.

205
00:16:26,840 --> 00:16:30,310
"Sorry?" he said, turning his attention to
Lynn.

206
00:16:30,310 --> 00:16:34,740
"A dance! Can we dance?" Lynn said impatiently.

207
00:16:34,740 --> 00:16:38,350
"Yes, sure. Sorry."

208
00:16:38,350 --> 00:16:43,110
They both got up and walked to the dance floor.
They held each other and danced slowly for

209
00:16:43,110 --> 00:16:49,070
the final verse of yet another song whose
name Eddie couldn't remember.

210
00:16:49,070 --> 00:16:53,310
Turning in the dance, Eddie was pleased that
Lynn was there with him as he tried to take

211
00:16:53,310 --> 00:16:58,100
in the fact that he was now staring at the
distant shape of Dominic Stephens, on the

212
00:16:58,100 --> 00:17:03,950
far side of the ship's dining room. The man,
Eddie saw, now turned to watch the dining

213
00:17:03,950 --> 00:17:10,740
room and the dancing. He was hidden in a fog
of his own cigar smoke. How Eddie had hated

214
00:17:10,740 --> 00:17:16,079
him. And how, after all this time, he still
hated him.

215
00:17:16,079 --> 00:17:17,339
The memories.

216
00:17:17,339 --> 00:17:18,470
The anger.

217
00:17:18,470 --> 00:17:20,530
The pain.

218
00:17:20,530 --> 00:17:27,120
"Are you sure you're feeling all right, Eddie?"
asked Lynn when they got back to their cabin.

219
00:17:27,120 --> 00:17:29,730
Eddie was sitting on the bed staring into
space.

220
00:17:29,730 --> 00:17:35,700
"Yes. Just tired. I think I'm still jet-lagged,
and I'm tired after walking on the island

221
00:17:35,700 --> 00:17:36,700
today."

222
00:17:36,700 --> 00:17:38,210
"You sure?"

223
00:17:38,210 --> 00:17:39,210
"Yes."

224
00:17:39,210 --> 00:17:43,460
"That trip on the glass-bottomed submarine
was amazing, wasn't it?"

225
00:17:43,460 --> 00:17:49,269
"Yeah," said Eddie. But he still couldn't
think straight. His mind was filling up more

226
00:17:49,269 --> 00:17:54,250
and more with the terrible realization that
Dominic was on the ship.

227
00:17:54,250 --> 00:18:00,159
Lynn knew him too well. "Eddie," she said,
sitting down beside him, taking his hand and

228
00:18:00,159 --> 00:18:06,120
looking at him. She stroked the back of his
head. "What's wrong?"

229
00:18:06,120 --> 00:18:11,169
Eddie had decided to accept that the trip
was now spoiled. Did he need to spoil it for

230
00:18:11,169 --> 00:18:16,850
his wife? She didn't have to know. They would
have their luxury cruise and go home to a

231
00:18:16,850 --> 00:18:23,160
new life. The ship was big enough. Dominic
and Eddie both looked older and Dominic probably

232
00:18:23,160 --> 00:18:27,009
wouldn't even remember him, so why worry about
it?

233
00:18:27,009 --> 00:18:31,309
But all the old feelings were there again,
and Eddie could sense his energy slipping

234
00:18:31,309 --> 00:18:37,490
away just thinking about it. It showed on
his face and Lynn could see it. Eddie could

235
00:18:37,490 --> 00:18:42,429
never hide much from his wife, and before
he knew it he found himself weakening.

236
00:18:42,429 --> 00:18:51,200
"It's Dominic. He's on the ship." It sounded
so strange to Eddie to even say those words.

237
00:18:51,200 --> 00:18:52,899
There was a pause.

238
00:18:52,899 --> 00:18:56,370
Lynn looked more closely at her husband.

239
00:18:56,370 --> 00:19:01,840
"What?" said Lynn quietly. "Dominic Stephens?
You're kidding."

240
00:19:01,840 --> 00:19:06,600
"I'm not kidding, Lynn. I wish I was," said
Eddie.

241
00:19:06,600 --> 00:19:09,830
"I haven't heard that name in a long time."

242
00:19:09,830 --> 00:19:11,110
"Well, he's here."

243
00:19:11,110 --> 00:19:13,460
"How do you know he's here?"

244
00:19:13,460 --> 00:19:18,110
"I saw him. He was sitting at the bar this
evening when we came in from the deck."

245
00:19:18,110 --> 00:19:22,881
"Eddie, we were sitting on the other side
of the dining room - you could hardly see

246
00:19:22,881 --> 00:19:25,260
anything. How can you be sure it was him?"

247
00:19:25,260 --> 00:19:35,750
"Oh, I'm sure, Lynn. No mistake. The same
fat, lazy bloke. But less hair now. And grey.

248
00:19:35,750 --> 00:19:37,440
And fatter."

249
00:19:37,440 --> 00:19:43,700
Lynn was still trying to take it in. "Dominic
Stephens is on this ship?"

250
00:19:43,700 --> 00:19:44,750
"Yes."

251
00:19:44,750 --> 00:19:49,179
She waited a moment. "Oh, Eddie."

252
00:19:49,179 --> 00:19:55,570
They both sat there for a moment. Then Lynn
spoke again. She was already recovering. "Well,

253
00:19:55,570 --> 00:20:02,120
look, it's a long time ago, Ed. It doesn't
matter any more. He doesn't matter any more.

254
00:20:02,120 --> 00:20:04,929
He's nothing. You don't have to talk to him."

255
00:20:04,929 --> 00:20:06,000
"I know."

256
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:11,179
"It's a big ship," Lynn continued. "It's extremely
unlikely you're going meet him..."

257
00:20:11,179 --> 00:20:14,379
"I saw him at the bar!" said Eddie.

258
00:20:14,379 --> 00:20:19,399
"... and even if you met him by chance, as
I said, he won't remember you." Then she looked

259
00:20:19,399 --> 00:20:24,940
closely at Eddie and asked softly, "You didn't
speak to him, did you?"

260
00:20:24,940 --> 00:20:28,179
"No," replied Eddie. "Of course not."

261
00:20:28,179 --> 00:20:31,149
"And did he see you?"

262
00:20:31,149 --> 00:20:36,600
"No." Eddie wasn't sure if Dominic had seen
him or not. Probably not. "Well, that's OK

263
00:20:36,600 --> 00:20:40,840
then," Lynn said, but she knew it was an unhelpful
thing to say.

264
00:20:40,840 --> 00:20:46,149
"It's not OK, Lynn. It's not OK at all. That
man is back."

265
00:20:46,149 --> 00:20:50,649
"He's not back. Try to calm down."

266
00:20:50,649 --> 00:20:55,230
"Calm down?!" said Eddie, raising his voice
and standing up. "We lost everything because

267
00:20:55,230 --> 00:21:00,860
of him, Lynn, everything - he cheated and
bullied and took it all away!"

268
00:21:00,860 --> 00:21:07,470
"Yes, I know, Ed, but it was sixteen years
ago. We've come a long way since then. You

269
00:21:07,470 --> 00:21:11,330
and Clive have each just put ten million quid
in the bank!"

270
00:21:11,330 --> 00:21:14,570
"So what? Dominic got away with it all at
Fenton's!"

271
00:21:14,570 --> 00:21:18,289
"It's all in the past. It doesn't matter anymore."

272
00:21:18,289 --> 00:21:24,700
"It does matter. He's still getting away with
it. He still looks very pleased with himself."

273
00:21:24,700 --> 00:21:30,650
"You don't know that. You don't know his life
now. I can't believe we're talking about all

274
00:21:30,650 --> 00:21:32,220
this after so long."

275
00:21:32,220 --> 00:21:37,150
"Because he's here, Lynn. On the ship. On
our cruise!"

276
00:21:37,150 --> 00:21:44,899
"Eddie, listen to me. Calm down. He and Neal
gave you a bad time, I know. But you fought

277
00:21:44,899 --> 00:21:51,320
back and survived, and you became successful
anyway. Without him. In spite of him and the

278
00:21:51,320 --> 00:21:57,409
things he said and did. You're here with me
now, on holiday, with financial security for

279
00:21:57,409 --> 00:22:04,559
the rest of our lives. You did it. You climbed
back out of the hole and it's OK. He can't

280
00:22:04,559 --> 00:22:06,039
hurt you anymore."

281
00:22:06,039 --> 00:22:08,549
"He nearly destroyed us, Lynn."

282
00:22:08,549 --> 00:22:12,919
"But he didn't, did he? We didn't let him."

283
00:22:12,919 --> 00:22:20,840
Eddie wiped the tears from his eyes. "I can't
believe he's on board! Why? He's still out

284
00:22:20,840 --> 00:22:23,960
there getting in the way. Spoiling everything."

285
00:22:23,960 --> 00:22:31,440
"He's not spoiling anything. Only if you let
him. You've come a long way since he pushed

286
00:22:31,440 --> 00:22:32,440
you out."

287
00:22:32,440 --> 00:22:38,940
"So why do I suddenly feel so angry? I can't
believe it. I think of him and those days

288
00:22:38,940 --> 00:22:44,190
at Fenton's from time to time, sometimes a
lot, and it never upsets me.

289
00:22:44,190 --> 00:22:50,549
"Well, you went through a tough time. It was
very hard. If you really did see him tonight,

290
00:22:50,549 --> 00:22:55,269
of course that's going to upset you. It's
not the same as the occasional memory."

291
00:22:55,269 --> 00:23:01,299
"Oh, I saw him all right. He still smokes
those hideous cigars."

292
00:23:01,299 --> 00:23:03,950
"OK," said Lynn.

293
00:23:03,950 --> 00:23:07,830
"You went through it too, you know," he reminded
her.

294
00:23:07,830 --> 00:23:09,669
"I know."

295
00:23:09,669 --> 00:23:10,789
Another pause.

296
00:23:10,789 --> 00:23:20,470
"We lost so much, Lynn: the house, the money.
Us. I was off sick for a year. A year!"

297
00:23:20,470 --> 00:23:26,539
"I know," said Lynn. "There's no getting away
from the damage the man caused. But you have

298
00:23:26,539 --> 00:23:32,259
to calm down. Nothing is going to happen.
You don't have to see him again or talk to

299
00:23:32,259 --> 00:23:33,259
him."

300
00:23:33,259 --> 00:23:37,830
"Well, what if he takes the same excursion
as us at some point? Or sits at our table

301
00:23:37,830 --> 00:23:38,830
for dinner?"

302
00:23:38,830 --> 00:23:46,760
"Eddie, there are almost 2,000 people on board.
It won't happen. We can ignore him. Being

303
00:23:46,760 --> 00:23:51,590
the sort of person Dominic is, he's probably
treated lots of people the way he treated

304
00:23:51,590 --> 00:23:55,990
you, so he won't know who you are or remember
what he did."

305
00:23:55,990 --> 00:23:58,320
"Somehow that makes it worse."

306
00:23:58,320 --> 00:24:04,200
"Well, there's nothing we can do about it.
If we see him again or he even recognizes

307
00:24:04,200 --> 00:24:08,559
you, we'll cross that bridge when we come
to it, all right?"

308
00:24:08,559 --> 00:24:10,139
Eddie was quiet.

309
00:24:10,139 --> 00:24:15,919
"All right?" Lynn repeated, holding his face
in her hands.

310
00:24:15,919 --> 00:24:18,630
"OK," said Eddie.

311
00:24:18,630 --> 00:24:22,980
CHAPTER FOUR
After the argument

312
00:24:22,980 --> 00:24:28,889
Eddie sat in a cafe not far from the office,
dipping his teaspoon into a large cappuccino,

313
00:24:28,889 --> 00:24:33,720
and tried to think of what he could do about
his job. He could leave, but that would mean

314
00:24:33,720 --> 00:24:39,570
giving in and letting Dominic have exactly
what he wanted. Besides, it would take several

315
00:24:39,570 --> 00:24:44,470
months, possibly a year, to find another good
job, and he would still have to put up with

316
00:24:44,470 --> 00:24:49,970
him in the meantime. He could officially complain
about Dominic's behavior. He had a strong

317
00:24:49,970 --> 00:24:56,820
case. But that would only make things worse.
Somehow Dominic had Gary, the CEO, on his

318
00:24:56,820 --> 00:25:01,999
side. And Ann Blake, the Financial Director,
would never support getting rid of Dominic,

319
00:25:01,999 --> 00:25:04,580
since she had hired him in the first place.

320
00:25:04,580 --> 00:25:11,619
"He's unbelievable. He actually said I was
too hands-on," said Eddie, stabbing at his

321
00:25:11,619 --> 00:25:13,350
drink with his spoon.

322
00:25:13,350 --> 00:25:18,640
"Really?" said Clive, who had left the office
and found Eddie sitting in the cafe.

323
00:25:18,640 --> 00:25:24,090
"Yes. He also said I wasn't a leader and that
Moscow was his deal."

324
00:25:24,090 --> 00:25:31,110
"You're joking," said Clive. He seemed genuinely
surprised. "That deal was yours. Everyone

325
00:25:31,110 --> 00:25:32,230
knows that."

326
00:25:32,230 --> 00:25:35,670
"Then he said my communication wasn't good
enough."

327
00:25:35,670 --> 00:25:43,010
"Eh? He can talk. He's got no people skills
whatsoever. Anyway, he never reads his emails."

328
00:25:43,010 --> 00:25:50,950
"I know. I told him that. He says I should
phone him," and Eddie laughed in disgust.

329
00:25:50,950 --> 00:25:52,940
"He's never there!"

330
00:25:52,940 --> 00:25:59,070
"Exactly! I said that too. It's pointless,
Clive. He doesn't listen and he interrupts

331
00:25:59,070 --> 00:26:03,869
all the time. He's so smug. He thinks he's
right about everything."

332
00:26:03,869 --> 00:26:09,170
"At least you're not alone. Everyone has the
same problem with him."

333
00:26:09,170 --> 00:26:11,510
"Well, what is his problem?"

334
00:26:11,510 --> 00:26:13,590
"It's obvious. He's insecure."

335
00:26:13,590 --> 00:26:17,090
"Well, it's not obvious when you're sitting
in a meeting with him."

336
00:26:17,090 --> 00:26:23,330
"He's a bully in a shirt and tie. All bullies
are insecure. Maybe his dad didn't show him

337
00:26:23,330 --> 00:26:27,119
any love. Maybe his dad's worse!"

338
00:26:27,119 --> 00:26:32,240
Eddie tried to smile as he looked out of the
window, as if the answer were out there somewhere.

339
00:26:32,240 --> 00:26:37,179
Maybe if he were to look long enough, the
answer would come and find him. He doubted

340
00:26:37,179 --> 00:26:39,909
it. He was exhausted.

341
00:26:39,909 --> 00:26:47,539
"Clive, how do they get to be in charge, these
people? They're utterly useless. He's useless."

342
00:26:47,539 --> 00:26:54,669
"Yes, and he knows it. Deep down. That's why
he picks on people and moves responsibility.

343
00:26:54,669 --> 00:26:57,049
No one actually knows what he does."

344
00:26:57,049 --> 00:27:01,570
"Yeah, and by the time they find out they
have to pay him a year's salary, and then

345
00:27:01,570 --> 00:27:03,100
he gets another job."

346
00:27:03,100 --> 00:27:08,919
"That's his skill, though. He talks well to
the top guys. But the real people don't respect

347
00:27:08,919 --> 00:27:13,299
him. I spoke to someone at Gallagher's the
other week, where Dominic worked for about

348
00:27:13,299 --> 00:27:15,529
two years. They said the same thing."

349
00:27:15,529 --> 00:27:20,519
"Do you think he has any idea what people
really think and say about him?"

350
00:27:20,519 --> 00:27:26,730
"No, I don't think he does. He's so superior
in his own mind he probably thinks we're all

351
00:27:26,730 --> 00:27:27,730
losers."

352
00:27:27,730 --> 00:27:34,630
"But he knows I'm good. He knows you're good
too, and that really irritates him, because

353
00:27:34,630 --> 00:27:40,700
we know this job and he doesn't. He just moves
tasks and people around all day and calls

354
00:27:40,700 --> 00:27:41,840
it strategy."

355
00:27:41,840 --> 00:27:45,269
"I know," said Clive.

356
00:27:45,269 --> 00:27:47,480
They both stared out of the window.

357
00:27:47,480 --> 00:27:54,539
"Did you hear what he said to Steve the other
day?" asked Clive. "No, what?"

358
00:27:54,539 --> 00:28:01,190
"'Dominic told Steve that he got the top job
because Ann and Gary saw him as a wise ambassador.'"

359
00:28:01,190 --> 00:28:07,009
"Wise? Ambassador? Ambassador for what?"

360
00:28:07,009 --> 00:28:10,149
"Who knows? He's in his own dream world."

361
00:28:10,149 --> 00:28:12,239
"Did he really say that?"

362
00:28:12,239 --> 00:28:17,780
"Yes. And when Steve questioned it, Dominic
then said he was older than anyone else anyway."

363
00:28:17,780 --> 00:28:19,129
"Unbelievable."

364
00:28:19,129 --> 00:28:25,149
"Who knows what he thinks? He's not like us.
I think that scares him."

365
00:28:25,149 --> 00:28:28,670
"Where do these people come from?"

366
00:28:28,670 --> 00:28:35,549
"I don't know, mate, but they soon move on.
We just have to hold on. Look on the bright

367
00:28:35,549 --> 00:28:39,409
side - it couldn't get any worse."

368
00:28:39,409 --> 00:28:45,850
But Eddie wasn't so sure. Eddie had the feeling
that things were going to get a lot worse.

369
00:28:45,850 --> 00:28:47,190
And he was right.

370
00:28:47,190 --> 00:28:54,239
Back at home, Eddie spent the evening trying
to catch up on the work he'd missed that afternoon,

371
00:28:54,239 --> 00:28:59,649
and looking at the many emails he had sent
Dominic. It was a nightmare.

372
00:28:59,649 --> 00:29:03,999
Again and again he considered walking away
from the job, but it hurt him more simply

373
00:29:03,999 --> 00:29:09,950
to give up. Besides, he was enjoying the Moscow
project, and he had done so much work for

374
00:29:09,950 --> 00:29:15,710
it. When he was in Moscow, he could get on
with things. He loved Russia and he loved

375
00:29:15,710 --> 00:29:22,120
the people there. It was such a different
world from the UK; and the owners of Zariya,

376
00:29:22,120 --> 00:29:29,009
Dima and Tatiana, always made him feel so
welcome. Over time Eddie had had to explain

377
00:29:29,009 --> 00:29:34,529
to them some of the difficulties back in London,
and they had been very helpful. Eddie was

378
00:29:34,529 --> 00:29:39,659
reading one of Dima's emails and smiling again
when Lynn walked into the room.

379
00:29:39,659 --> 00:29:42,749
"Will you be much longer?" asked Lynn.

380
00:29:42,749 --> 00:29:48,529
"Maybe. I'm behind on some deadlines, and
today's battle with Dominic didn't help."

381
00:29:48,529 --> 00:29:51,879
"Just leave it now, Ed. Come to bed," said
Lynn.

382
00:29:51,879 --> 00:29:55,649
"I can't. There's so much. Too much."

383
00:29:55,649 --> 00:30:01,450
"There's always too much," Lynn replied. "It
will still be there in the morning. Give yourself

384
00:30:01,450 --> 00:30:02,450
a break."

385
00:30:02,450 --> 00:30:08,340
"Yeah, well, that's true, but with Dominic
I have to be extra careful. He picks on everything."

386
00:30:08,340 --> 00:30:10,169
"He's an idiot."

387
00:30:10,169 --> 00:30:16,139
"Yeah, I know it, and you know it, and everyone
else knows it, but he's still the boss."

388
00:30:16,139 --> 00:30:19,659
"Well, what I mean is just ignore him."

389
00:30:19,659 --> 00:30:25,380
"How can I ignore him, Lynn? He's the boss!
He runs the division. He runs me."

390
00:30:25,380 --> 00:30:27,759
"Well, don't let him," said Lynn.

391
00:30:27,759 --> 00:30:33,730
"I'm not letting him!" shouted Eddie. "I'm
trying to stop him. That's the problem!"

392
00:30:33,730 --> 00:30:36,929
"There's no need to shout, Eddie. I'm not
deaf."

393
00:30:36,929 --> 00:30:39,200
"Well, you're not being very helpful."

394
00:30:39,200 --> 00:30:45,450
"Thanks a lot," she said sarcastically. "I'm
doing my best."

395
00:30:45,450 --> 00:30:50,970
"Sorry. I was hired to build a team, win a
project like the one in Moscow and make things

396
00:30:50,970 --> 00:30:56,519
profitable. He was brought in to oversee the
whole division. Then he gets bonuses for doing

397
00:30:56,519 --> 00:31:00,360
very little, and I get the blame when the
numbers suddenly don't add up."

398
00:31:00,360 --> 00:31:02,399
"Your numbers are fine."

399
00:31:02,399 --> 00:31:04,970
"Not according to Dominic."

400
00:31:04,970 --> 00:31:05,970
"Why?"

401
00:31:05,970 --> 00:31:12,690
"Oh, well, during our useless meeting today,
he brought up that old story about being 25,000

402
00:31:12,690 --> 00:31:18,230
pounds over budget, when everyone knows he
fixed the numbers. Somehow he gets his bonuses

403
00:31:18,230 --> 00:31:24,169
and puts any blame on me. I'm almost certain
now that he wants me out, Lynn."

404
00:31:24,169 --> 00:31:30,730
"Surely not. He needs you. If it weren't for
you, good people would have left ages ago.

405
00:31:30,730 --> 00:31:33,570
Besides, who else could move Russia along?"

406
00:31:33,570 --> 00:31:35,220
"Oh, don't mention Russia."

407
00:31:35,220 --> 00:31:38,470
"Why? That's your big success story."

408
00:31:38,470 --> 00:31:45,100
"Oh, he keeps going on about the fact that
he won the Moscow contract, not me."

409
00:31:45,100 --> 00:31:47,240
"What? That's just not true."

410
00:31:47,240 --> 00:31:48,769
"I know."

411
00:31:48,769 --> 00:31:53,109
"What about Ann and Gary? Can't you talk to
them about all this?"

412
00:31:53,109 --> 00:31:59,769
"They've changed, Lynn. I've hardly seen them
since the new partners came in. Besides, Gary

413
00:31:59,769 --> 00:32:06,220
and Dominic are always playing golf at the
weekends. Ann's OK still, but she's very political,

414
00:32:06,220 --> 00:32:10,970
and I think she's embarrassed that Dominic's
upsetting everyone. After all, she was the

415
00:32:10,970 --> 00:32:12,639
one who recruited him."

