00:47:21,240 --> 00:47:23,760
"Maxine's doing that now."

627
00:47:23,760 --> 00:47:28,360
"Maxine shouldn't be doing that sort of thing.
She's only a temp."

628
00:47:28,360 --> 00:47:32,520
"Well, she sometimes takes phone calls for
us in the office and sets UP meetings."

629
00:47:32,520 --> 00:47:39,441
"She's not a secretary, Eddie, she's a student!
She types in data. You can't ask her to phone

630
00:47:39,441 --> 00:47:40,970
our biggest customers..."

631
00:47:40,970 --> 00:47:46,690
Eddie's face was red, he could feel it. Already
things were out of control.

632
00:47:46,690 --> 00:47:50,320
"She's only setting up a conference call,"
he said.

633
00:47:50,320 --> 00:47:53,580
"Do it yourself," said Dominic impatiently.

634
00:47:53,580 --> 00:47:57,540
"Fine," Eddie. It wasn't fine at all.

635
00:47:57,540 --> 00:48:01,900
"And copy me in on the schedule. I want to
join the call."

636
00:48:01,900 --> 00:48:02,900
"Why?"

637
00:48:02,900 --> 00:48:07,400
"I want to find out when Dima's going to order
the rest of the software for all the offices

638
00:48:07,400 --> 00:48:08,400
in the region."

639
00:48:08,400 --> 00:48:14,220
"Dominic, please leave that to me. This call
is more for product training and looking at

640
00:48:14,220 --> 00:48:19,740
any specific problems so far. I don't want
to distract him with pressure for more orders.

641
00:48:19,740 --> 00:48:21,480
We have time for that."

642
00:48:21,480 --> 00:48:23,480
"We don't have time, Eddie."

643
00:48:23,480 --> 00:48:29,070
"Yes, we do. At least until my next visit
to Moscow. That's when we will be looking

644
00:48:29,070 --> 00:48:33,920
at the next orders. As a matter of fact I've
got a meeting with Neal in Production today

645
00:48:33,920 --> 00:48:34,920
to look at costs."

646
00:48:34,920 --> 00:48:40,530
There was a knock on the door and Neal Skinner,
Head of Production, walked into the office.

647
00:48:40,530 --> 00:48:47,480
"Well, well. Here he is!" said Dominic. "Come
in, Neal. We were just talking about you."

648
00:48:47,480 --> 00:48:53,480
"Nothing bad, I hope," said Neal. His smile
was insincere.

649
00:48:53,480 --> 00:48:59,660
He was a very tall, thin man who always looked
pale and wore dull suits. The Grey Man, they

650
00:48:59,660 --> 00:49:04,830
called him in the office. Neal was Eddie's
main contact in Production for all things

651
00:49:04,830 --> 00:49:07,510
related to the Moscow project.

652
00:49:07,510 --> 00:49:13,551
He was a cold character who took himself very
seriously and had little sense of humor. Like

653
00:49:13,551 --> 00:49:19,840
Dominic, he had a superior manner and was
stubborn. When engaged in conversation he

654
00:49:19,840 --> 00:49:25,090
looked at the other person critically, judging
them negatively. Neal always tried to give

655
00:49:25,090 --> 00:49:30,140
the impression that he knew everyone and that
he was in charge, but it was clear he was

656
00:49:30,140 --> 00:49:35,630
not really comfortable in his role and didn't
really know what he was doing. He hid behind

657
00:49:35,630 --> 00:49:40,520
business jargon, name-dropping and things
he had learned from going on too many training

658
00:49:40,520 --> 00:49:46,470
courses. But bosses liked him. Employees and
customers did not. They thought he was a waste

659
00:49:46,470 --> 00:49:49,970
of time. Eddie knew he was a waste of time.

660
00:49:49,970 --> 00:49:53,110
"Neal, thanks for joining us."

661
00:49:53,110 --> 00:49:59,440
"No problem," Neal replied. So agreeable.
So good with a boss around. Neal crossed his

662
00:49:59,440 --> 00:50:02,260
long legs and folded his arms.

663
00:50:02,260 --> 00:50:06,230
Eddie now had a feeling that this meeting
had been arranged, and that Neal was part

664
00:50:06,230 --> 00:50:10,490
of it. It was no coincidence that he had turned
up at that point.

665
00:50:10,490 --> 00:50:15,480
"Did you see the match last night?" Neal asked
Dominic. Still no smile.

666
00:50:15,480 --> 00:50:21,281
"No, I missed it. I heard that new defender
Slater scored an own goal and saved us. That

667
00:50:21,281 --> 00:50:23,170
was very kind, thank you."

668
00:50:23,170 --> 00:50:26,030
"We're still five points ahead of you, though."

669
00:50:26,030 --> 00:50:30,980
"Not for long. You've got Chelsea on Saturday,
and then you're away to Liverpool the following

670
00:50:30,980 --> 00:50:32,110
week."

671
00:50:32,110 --> 00:50:37,790
"Gentlemen," interrupted Eddie, "if it's OK
with you... could we get back to business?"

672
00:50:37,790 --> 00:50:44,940
"The thing is, Eddie," said Dominic, "we need
more people on the Moscow account..."

673
00:50:44,940 --> 00:50:48,980
Eddie wasn't sure where this was going, but
he was slightly encouraged by the possibility

674
00:50:48,980 --> 00:50:54,780
of getting more assistance. "Right. That's
good," he said, trying to be positive. "We're

675
00:50:54,780 --> 00:51:00,310
short-staffed, as you know, and we could use
more help." But he still wasn't sure why Neal

676
00:51:00,310 --> 00:51:07,290
was there - he remained still and quiet, looking
first at Dominic and then at Eddie.

677
00:51:07,290 --> 00:51:12,960
"... so Neal has agreed to take charge and
give you guys a hand." Dominic looked back

678
00:51:12,960 --> 00:51:18,400
at his computer screen, then tapped something
on his keyboard. Eddie looked at Neal.

679
00:51:18,400 --> 00:51:23,220
"Take charge of what, exactly?" he asked,
looking back at Dominic.

680
00:51:23,220 --> 00:51:29,540
"Take charge of the account. In Moscow." Dominic
gave a little laugh.

681
00:51:29,540 --> 00:51:35,690
Eddie went cold. He could feel the sharp blade
of realization enter his back. "Are you moving

682
00:51:35,690 --> 00:51:39,350
to Moscow, Neal?" he asked, confused but hopeful.

683
00:51:39,350 --> 00:51:46,400
"No, mate. I'm staying in London." Neal smiled
his superior smile.

684
00:51:46,400 --> 00:51:51,230
Eddie did not like the sound of this. He didn't
like being laughed at either.

685
00:51:51,230 --> 00:51:56,290
Eddie turned his attention to Dominic. "Dominic,
I don't quite follow. What's going on?"

686
00:51:56,290 --> 00:52:01,690
"I've decided to make some changes in the
team. Neal has a lot of experience in this

687
00:52:01,690 --> 00:52:06,830
field, so you will report to him. He is now
Head of Product and Business Development.

688
00:52:06,830 --> 00:52:10,590
It's a new position."

689
00:52:10,590 --> 00:52:15,510
Neal kept his eyes on Dominic the whole time.
He looked very pleased with himself, as if

690
00:52:15,510 --> 00:52:18,090
he was waiting to be given a trophy of some
sort.

691
00:52:18,090 --> 00:52:21,320
'It makes sense, Eddie. Really," said Neal.

692
00:52:21,320 --> 00:52:26,780
"I'm not interested in your opinion," snapped
Eddie. He was trying to stay calm but inside

693
00:52:26,780 --> 00:52:32,720
he was ready to explode. He tried to keep
his voice steady. He leaned forward on Dominic's

694
00:52:32,720 --> 00:52:35,060
desk and looked him in the eye.

695
00:52:35,060 --> 00:52:39,180
"So what's my position?" he asked.

696
00:52:39,180 --> 00:52:41,770
CHAPTER SEVEN
An encounter in Barbados

697
00:52:41,770 --> 00:52:50,210
The Parvina docked quietly at Bridgetown,
Barbados, at 7.20 a.m. Eddie and Lynn were

698
00:52:50,210 --> 00:52:55,750
already awake and they lay in bed listening
to the radio. At 7.30 there was a knock on

699
00:52:55,750 --> 00:52:56,750
the door.

700
00:52:56,750 --> 00:52:59,710
"Good morning. Breakfast," said the voice
outside.

701
00:52:59,710 --> 00:53:04,940
Eddie got out of bed, almost believing he
would step into cold water once more, and

702
00:53:04,940 --> 00:53:11,280
opened the door. A young, smiling man brought
in a large tray full of cereals, orange juice,

703
00:53:11,280 --> 00:53:16,710
pastries and a cafeteria of coffee. Eddie
led him through the cabin to the balcony door,

704
00:53:16,710 --> 00:53:20,490
which he opened. The humid air struck him
immediately.

705
00:53:20,490 --> 00:53:27,710
"Phew, it's warm. Leave the tray inside,"
he said to the man. "Thanks." Eddie gave him

706
00:53:27,710 --> 00:53:31,200
a few dollars and the man left.

707
00:53:31,200 --> 00:53:35,830
Eddie looked out across the harbour view to
where blue sea met white sand, to the houses

708
00:53:35,830 --> 00:53:41,670
dotted about the town, and to the green palm
trees inland. Market stalls were already being

709
00:53:41,670 --> 00:53:47,570
set up near the ship, where locals could sell
souvenirs and fruit to the passengers. Eddie

710
00:53:47,570 --> 00:53:52,740
heard the distinctive metallic sound of a
steel band and saw five boys playing down

711
00:53:52,740 --> 00:53:59,000
below. He could see at least three other ships
in the harbour. Given his nightmare, he really

712
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:02,330
appreciated the fact that this was the reality.

713
00:54:02,330 --> 00:54:07,500
"Good morning, Mrs Millionaire. Another day
in paradise," he said.

714
00:54:07,500 --> 00:54:12,000
"What's for breakfast?" asked Lynn, yawning.

715
00:54:12,000 --> 00:54:14,580
"Get up and have a look."

716
00:54:14,580 --> 00:54:17,400
"You seem very awake and lively," she said.

717
00:54:17,400 --> 00:54:21,930
"Yes, well, after last night's trip to hell
and back, this comes as a relief."

718
00:54:21,930 --> 00:54:25,750
"You were in a terrible state. Do you remember?"

719
00:54:25,750 --> 00:54:31,070
"Yes. I'm trying not to think about it," said
Eddie. And he really was trying not to think

720
00:54:31,070 --> 00:54:36,700
about it - about the dream, about Dominic
Stephens, about the real nightmare of sixteen

721
00:54:36,700 --> 00:54:39,960
years ago. But he knew it wouldn't be easy.

722
00:54:39,960 --> 00:54:44,860
"Damn him," he said under his breath.

723
00:54:44,860 --> 00:54:49,180
Lynn and Eddie had decided to do different
things that day. Eddie had chosen to go on

724
00:54:49,180 --> 00:54:55,060
a catamaran and snorkeling trip in the morning,
while Lynn had booked tennis lessons. They

725
00:54:55,060 --> 00:54:59,930
took a taxi to the Tropical Beach Hotel and
Spa, where they were welcomed with fruit punch

726
00:54:59,930 --> 00:55:04,170
and given a short talk about the area by one
of the hotel guides.

727
00:55:04,170 --> 00:55:10,410
The catamaran was scheduled to depart from
the hotel's private beach at 10.30 a.m., and

728
00:55:10,410 --> 00:55:15,270
Eddie put on his life jacket and joined several
other passengers and hotel guests for the

729
00:55:15,270 --> 00:55:21,090
two-hour trip. He was given a mask, snorkel
and fins, and he waved to Lynn as he walked

730
00:55:21,090 --> 00:55:26,160
down to where the boat was tied up. He was
carrying his deck shoes and had a towel in

731
00:55:26,160 --> 00:55:33,010
his hand as he made his way, barefoot, across
the fine, smooth sand.

732
00:55:33,010 --> 00:55:37,590
As he waited his turn to get on board, he
looked down at his feet in the warm, green

733
00:55:37,590 --> 00:55:42,540
water and thought again about the nightmare
and about Dominic. He wondered where Dominic

734
00:55:42,540 --> 00:55:47,850
was today. Was he on a trip? Was he even still
on board?

735
00:55:47,850 --> 00:55:52,020
In the taxi on the way to the hotel, Eddie
had worried that Dominic would be on the same

736
00:55:52,020 --> 00:55:58,130
excursion. But how likely was it that he would
meet him? He started feeling angry again that

737
00:55:58,130 --> 00:56:02,360
Dominic was on the ship. And that he still
existed at all.

738
00:56:02,360 --> 00:56:07,360
In spite of this, Eddie was able to relax
during the boat trip. After an hour of sailing

739
00:56:07,360 --> 00:56:13,090
around the bay and past some spectacular beaches
and coves, the catamaran dropped anchor and

740
00:56:13,090 --> 00:56:19,080
the small group went snorkeling near an old
shipwreck. They watched and fed some stingrays,

741
00:56:19,080 --> 00:56:23,880
and Eddie enjoyed the calming effect of being
below the surface and in a very different

742
00:56:23,880 --> 00:56:29,630
world underwater. He was a good swimmer and
very fit. He had swum for his school and his

743
00:56:29,630 --> 00:56:35,670
university, and he had won medals for long-distance
swimming. Even now, at home, he tried to get

744
00:56:35,670 --> 00:56:38,850
to the local pool at least twice a week.

745
00:56:38,850 --> 00:56:43,520
When he got back to the beach hotel, he was
feeling tired but refreshed. He'd caught the

746
00:56:43,520 --> 00:56:49,250
sun too, and his forehead and nose were burnt.
He found Lynn sitting on a sun lounger by

747
00:56:49,250 --> 00:56:54,060
a small pool with fountains. She was reading
and sipping another fruit punch.

748
00:56:54,060 --> 00:56:58,110
"Hello, you. I thought I'd find you here,"
he said.

749
00:56:58,110 --> 00:57:00,630
"Oh, hi. How was it?"

750
00:57:00,630 --> 00:57:01,630
"Brilliant."

751
00:57:01,630 --> 00:57:03,710
"You've caught the sun."

752
00:57:03,710 --> 00:57:08,840
"I know. I forgot to take some decent sun
block. I borrowed some off the guys on the

753
00:57:08,840 --> 00:57:11,000
boat, but I think it was too late."

754
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:17,641
"Here," she said, reaching for some cream
in her bag. "Use some of this." She passed

755
00:57:17,641 --> 00:57:22,400
him a tube of cream and Eddie squeezed some
into his hand and rubbed it on his face.

756
00:57:22,400 --> 00:57:24,720
"How was the tennis?" he asked.

757
00:57:24,720 --> 00:57:29,030
"It was cancelled. The guy never turned up,
and it was too late to get another trainer."

758
00:57:29,030 --> 00:57:33,380
"Really? That's not good. We've already paid
for it."

759
00:57:33,380 --> 00:57:39,250
"I know," said Lynn, "but they're giving us
lunch for free instead, so I don't mind really.

760
00:57:39,250 --> 00:57:43,000
I'm booked for tennis again in St Lucia in
a few days, so that's OK."

761
00:57:43,000 --> 00:57:49,130
He mocked her: "Listen to you! I 'm booked
for tennis again in St Lucia in a few days,

762
00:57:49,130 --> 00:57:54,520
she says, sipping her cocktail." Then he said,
"This is the life, eh?"

763
00:57:54,520 --> 00:57:58,080
"It certainly is. Oh, look, here's Jen."

764
00:57:58,080 --> 00:58:02,830
"Who's Jen?" asked Eddie, looking around.
He thought she looked familiar.

765
00:58:02,830 --> 00:58:07,650
"She was booked for the tennis as well, so
we came here for a drink instead and we started

766
00:58:07,650 --> 00:58:09,700
chatting. You'll never guess who she is."

767
00:58:09,700 --> 00:58:12,800
"I know her, don't I?" asked Eddie.

768
00:58:12,800 --> 00:58:16,770
"Yes and no. The same thing happened to me
when I first saw her."

769
00:58:16,770 --> 00:58:23,220
"She's from the ship. She must be," he said.
Jen was almost at the pool where they were

770
00:58:23,220 --> 00:58:24,220
sitting.

771
00:58:24,220 --> 00:58:27,190
"Yes. Not only that. She's the singer in the
band!"

772
00:58:27,190 --> 00:58:33,830
"Oh yes!" said Eddie, turning to meet her.
She had on wide sunglasses and a baseball

773
00:58:33,830 --> 00:58:38,910
cap. She wore a colourful sarong with palm
tree patterns, and her T-shirt was orange

774
00:58:38,910 --> 00:58:44,000
with a black saxophone logo. She was carrying
a drink in one hand and a cigarette in the

775
00:58:44,000 --> 00:58:45,000
other.

776
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:49,070
"Hi, Lynn. Is this your man then?" asked Jen.

777
00:58:49,070 --> 00:58:51,790
"Yes, this is Eddie. Eddie, this is Jen."

778
00:58:51,790 --> 00:58:57,250
"Nice to meet you, Jen," Eddie said, shaking
her hand.

779
00:58:57,250 --> 00:59:00,110
"Likewise," she said. "How was the boat trip?"

780
00:59:00,110 --> 00:59:05,470
"Great, thanks. They took us around some fabulous
beaches. Then we stopped and swam off the

781
00:59:05,470 --> 00:59:06,890
reef near an old shipwreck."

782
00:59:06,890 --> 00:59:09,350
"Cool!" said Jen.

783
00:59:09,350 --> 00:59:12,880
"Some stingrays came by and we were given
some food for them."

784
00:59:12,880 --> 00:59:17,910
"Oh, I'd love to do that, but I'd be terrified,"
said Jen.

785
00:59:17,910 --> 00:59:21,710
"They're not that dangerous actually, although
they can give you a nasty bite."

786
00:59:21,710 --> 00:59:23,870
"Ugh!" said Lynn.

787
00:59:23,870 --> 00:59:26,700
"Or sting with their tail," added Jen.

788
00:59:26,700 --> 00:59:31,710
"Yeah, well, that's true. It's rare, though,"
said Eddie. "That usually happens if you stand

789
00:59:31,710 --> 00:59:34,280
on one when they're buried in the sand in
shallow water."

790
00:59:34,280 --> 00:59:39,010
"Aren't you afraid of sharks?" asked Jen,
lifting up her sunglasses.

791
00:59:39,010 --> 00:59:43,180
"I try not to stand on sharks," said Eddie,
smiling.

792
00:59:43,180 --> 00:59:44,410
"You know what I mean."

793
00:59:44,410 --> 00:59:49,490
"There weren't any in the area we were in,"
said Eddie, sitting down on a sun lounger

794
00:59:49,490 --> 00:59:51,140
next to his wife.

795
00:59:51,140 --> 00:59:53,580
"How do you know?" asked Lynn.

796
00:59:53,580 --> 00:59:56,690
"Well, you don't. You have to hope that there
aren't any."

797
00:59:56,690 --> 00:59:59,020
"You must be mad," said Jen.

798
00:59:59,020 --> 01:00:03,620
"It's worth it. The fish you can see near
the reef are so beautiful."

799
01:00:03,620 --> 01:00:08,650
"Well, Jen and I have been doing as little
as possible, haven't we, Jen?"

800
01:00:08,650 --> 01:00:12,850
"Absolutely," said Jen, sitting back on her
lounger and sipping her drink.

801
01:00:12,850 --> 01:00:16,120
"So, no tennis, then?" asked Eddie.

802
01:00:16,120 --> 01:00:19,690
"No," said Jen. "But we get a free lunch,"
she added.

803
01:00:19,690 --> 01:00:23,790
"So I heard," said Eddie. "What are you doing
later?"

804
01:00:23,790 --> 01:00:27,300
"Well, my partner will be here soon and we're
booked to go on the Island Safari."

805
01:00:27,300 --> 01:00:32,370
"Oh, I saw that in the brochure," said Lynn.
"Is that the trip where you get a private

